{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605011"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:01:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:01:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15859"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15859"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.43,0.09,0.17,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62921"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8550"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8580"},{"type":"tags","id":"10556"},{"type":"tags","id":"10610"},{"type":"tags","id":"10611"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20516"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62921"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA spermatozoon must undergo several important changes and overcome multiple barriers before it can successfully fertilise an oocyte.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes a process involved in sperm-oocyte interaction during fertilisation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sperm penetration requires potassium-dependent enzymes","Sperm hyaluronidase removes the corona radiata","Sperm capacitation requires 24 hours to complete","Sperm acrosin removes the corona radiata","Sperm capacitation occurs in the epididymis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Esperm hyaluronidase removes the corona radiata\u003C/strong\u003E. This enzyme specifically breaks down hyaluronic acid in the outer layer of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESperm penetration\u003C/strong\u003E requires calcium-dependent enzymes, rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Epotassium-dependent \u003C/strong\u003Eenzymes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESperm capacitation\u003C/strong\u003E takes 5-7 hours in humans, not \u003Cstrong\u003E24 hours\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESperm acrosin\u003C/strong\u003E does not remove the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorona radiata \u003C/strong\u003E- this is the role of hyaluronidase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESperm capacitation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the female reproductive tract, not in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eepididymis\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Capacitation occurs in the female reproductive tract and takes 5-7 hours in humans","The corona radiata is removed by hyaluronidase during sperm penetration","The acrosome reaction releases enzymes that digest the zona pellucida"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Zafar MI, Lu S, Li H. Sperm-oocyte interplay: an overview of spermatozoon\u2019s rol